"I'll iterate through all nodes. 
Whenever I find an unvisited node, I'll start a DFS from it and increment my component count. 
That DFS will mark the entire connected component as visited."

The Master Pattern

You will use this exact pattern in:

Graphs
Number of Connected Components
Provinces
Connected Cities
Grids
Number of Islands
Count Sub-Islands
Closed Islands
Distinct Islands
Other Variants
Friend Circles
Network Connectivity

The pattern is always:

for(each node/cell) {

    if(not visited) {

        count++;

        dfs(...);
    }
}

Code

int countComponents(int n,
                    List<List<Integer>> graph)
{
    boolean[] visited = new boolean[n];

    int count = 0;

    for(int node = 0; node < n; node++) {

        if(!visited[node]) {

            count++;

            dfs(node, graph, visited);
        }
    }

    return count;
}

Interview Insight

Many graph problems are secretly:

"How many times do I need to start a new DFS?"

That's often the whole solution.